did not always erupt into hostilities but that people also had to arrange themselves with divided loyalties – between the old faith and the new, between religious and secular interests, between officially sanctioned and privately held beliefs. What role might literature have played here? Can we conceive of literary representations as possible sites of de-escalation? Do different discursive, aesthetic, or social contexts inflect or deflect the demands of religious loyalties? Such questions open a new perspective on post-Reformation English culture and literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aFaith. 0aReligion and literaturezEnglandxHistoryvCongresses. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aChristian faith.  aChristmas celebrations.  aElizabethan romances.  aEucharist debate.  aJohn Donne.  aconfessional conflict.  aearly modern England.  agoodnight ballads.  ainterrogative conscience.  aliterary form.  aperformative negotiation.  areligious conflict.  areligious reform.  areligious ritual.  atragic mediation.  awitchcraft.1 aBaldo, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldo, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBlackstone, Mary A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlock, Alexandra M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooke, Conti, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDodson, Joel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJensen, Phebe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarremann, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https: